SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 613
By Oliver
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend The Tennessee Tribune
on the occasion of its thirty-fifth anniversary.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should recognize those outstanding newspapers
throughout the State of Tennessee that endeavor to provide exceptional news coverage and
serve community needs and interests by means of poignant and thorough journalism; and
WHEREAS, The Tennessee Tribune celebrates its thirty-fifth anniversary this year,
marking three and one-half decades of devoted service to Nashville's African-American
community; and
WHEREAS, this important regional newspaper is the life's work and legacy of Rosetta
Irvin Miller-Perry, who established the weekly missive in 1991 after retiring from a career with
the United States government, having served with the United States Commission on Civil Rights
and as Director of the United States Equal Employment Opportunity Commission under
Clarence Thomas; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Miller-Perry, the daughter of Anderson and Mary Irvin, was born in
Coraopolis, Pennsylvania, and graduated from Coraopolis Senior High School before serving in
the United States Military; she was among the first African-American students to graduate from
Memphis State University, now the University of Memphis, and went on to attend Howard
University Law School; and
WHEREAS, in 1990, she founded Perry & Perry & Associates, Inc., and launched
Contempora Magazine; the following year, she founded The Tennessee Tribune, a newspaper
highlighting the African-American and minority community locally, regionally, and nationally,
which became one of the approximately 200 African-American newspapers that were being
published nationwide at the time; and
