WHEREAS, denied funds from local banks, Rosetta Miller-Perry invested $70,000 from
her personal savings to launch The Tennessee Tribune and watched as it became one of the
most influential African-American publications in the State; and
WHEREAS, within five years, Ms. Miller-Perry purchased her first building on Morena
Street; however, her desire to be located in the heart of the African-American community led her
to purchase and renovate a building on historic Jefferson Street—the historic Universal
Insurance Building, which still houses the newspaper today; and
WHEREAS, under Ms. Miller-Perry's astute guidance, The Tennessee Tribune has
become the most effective African-American weekly publication in Middle Tennessee,
continuing to champion the cause of Civil Rights and the voices and leadership of African
Americans; and
WHEREAS, we find it appropriate to recognize and commend Ms. Miller-Perry and all
who have contributed to The Tennessee Tribune for their unstinting dedication to providing
Tennesseans with exceptional news coverage of an unparalleled caliber; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor founder Rosetta Irvin Miller-Perry and
staff, past and present, of The Tennessee Tribune on the occasion of the newspaper's thirty-fifth
anniversary, commending their meritorious service to the State of Tennessee in their
unwavering pursuit of presenting exemplary news coverage.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
